@node RX_CBREAD "TTManager ARexx:  ReadClip"
@toc AREXX

@{u}@{b}ReadClip@{ub}@{uu}
  Copies the contents of the current clipboard unit into a compound variable.


@{b}Usage:@{ub}
  ReadClip <stem>

    <stem> - Variable to hold clipboard contents.


@{b}Results:@{ub}
<stem>.count - Number of lines of text.
<stem>.0 to <stem>.count-1 - Clipboard text.

rc     - Always 0 (OK).
result - Not used.


@{b}Example:@{ub}
  /* Print clip unit 0's contents */
  'SETCLIPUNIT 0'
  'READCLIP cb'

  SAY cb.count 'lines.'

  DO i = 0 TO cb.count - 1
    SAY cb.i
  END
@endnode


@node RX_TTLREV "TTManager ARexx:  ReverseTooltypeList"
@toc AREXX

@{u}@{b}ReverseTooltypeList@{ub}@{uu}
  Reverses the order of the tooltypes in the tooltype list.  The last
tooltype becomes the first, etc.

* This command requires a TTManager window to be open.


@{b}Usage:@{ub}
  ReverseTooltypeList


@{b}Results:@{ub}
rc     - 5 (WARN) = No open windows.
result - Not used.


@{b}Example:@{ub}
  Beginning tooltype list:  Zero
                            One
        Current tooltype -> Two
                            Three

'REVERSETOOLTYPELIST'


        New tooltype list:  Three
        Current tooltype -> Two
                            One
                            Zero
@endnode


@node RX_REQCH "TTManager ARexx:  RequestChoice"
@toc AREXX

@{u}@{b}RequestChoice@{ub}@{uu}
  Opens a requester, displaying some text and buttons.


@{b}Usage:@{ub}
  RequestChoice TITLE <text> BODY <text> [BUTTONS <text>]

    TITLE <text> - The requester's title.

    BODY <text> - Text to appear inside the requester.

    BUTTONS <text> - Seperate buttons with the "|" character.
                     Ex:  "Yes|Maybe|No"
                     If omitted, one button named "Okay" will be displayed.

@{b}Notes:@{ub}
  - Enclose in quotation marks any text containing spaces.
  - Use "*n" to insert a linefeed.


@{b}Results:@{ub}
rc     - Always 0 (OK).
result - The number of the button the user pressed.
         The rightmost button (usually the cancel option) is number "0", thus
        the buttons are numbered:  1, 2, 3, ..., 0.
@endnode


@node RX_STATE "TTManager ARexx:  SetTooltypeState"
@toc AREXX

@{u}@{b}SetTooltypeState@{ub}@{uu}
  Adds or removes parentheses around a tooltype, thus making it active or
inactive.


@{b}Usage:@{ub}
  SetTooltypeState [<num> | ALL] [ON=ACTIVE | OFF=INACTIVE | TOGGLE]

    <num> - The tooltype to modify.  0 = First tooltype.
            Defaults to the current tooltype.

      ALL - Modify the entire tooltype list.

      ACTIVE - Make the tooltype active (remove any bracketing parentheses).

      INACTIVE - Encloses the tooltype in parentheses.

      TOGGLE - Inactive tooltypes become avtive, and vice-versa.


@{b}Results:@{ub}
rc     - 5 (WARN) = No open windows.
result - Not used.


@{b}Example:@{ub}
  Beginning tooltype list:  TOPEDGE=15
                            (CLOSEWORKBENCH=YES)
                            AUTOSAVE=ON

'SETTOOLTYPESTATE ALL TOGGLE'

        New tooltype list:  (TOPEDGE=15)
                            CLOSEWORKBENCH=YES
                            (AUTOSAVE=ON)
@endnode


@node RX_TTSORT "TTManager ARexx:  SortTooltypeList"
@toc AREXX

@{u}@{b}SortTooltypeList@{ub}@{uu}
  As the name implies, this sorts the tooltype list.  Tooltypes are sorted
alphabetically, by their keywords.  The tooltype's value (if it has one) and
whether or not it's disabled is ignorred.


@{b}Usage:@{ub}
  SortTooltypeList


@{b}Results:@{ub}
rc     - 5 (WARN) = No open windows.
result - Not used.


@{b}Example:@{ub}
  Beginning tooltype list:  TOPEDGE=15
                            (CLOSEWORKBENCH=YES)
                            AUTOSAVE=ON

'SORTTOOLTYPELIST'

       New tooltype list:   AUTOSAVE=ON
                            (CLOSEWORKBENCH=YES)
                            TOPEDGE=15
@endnode


